OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
ProjectName: Stream Monitoring in Klamath Network Parks
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 5310 B ~ Total Organic Carbon by Combustion-Infrared Method
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

ProjectName: Stream Monitoring in Klamath Network Parks
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.

ProjectName: Stream Monitoring in Klamath Network Parks
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 3111 B ~ Metals in Water by FLAA- Direct Air-Acetylene Flame
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
ProjectName: Stream Monitoring in Klamath Network Parks
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 5310 B ~ Total Organic Carbon by Combustion-Infrared Method
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 445.0 ~ EPA; Chlorophyll and Pheophytin in Algae by Fluorescence
LaboratoryName: Cascade Research Group

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 3111 B ~ Metals in Water by FLAA- Direct Air-Acetylene Flame
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4500 P F ~ Phosphorus in Water by Colorimetry Automated Ascorbic Acid Method
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 445.0 ~ EPA; Chlorophyll and Pheophytin in Algae by Fluorescence
LaboratoryName: Cascade Research Group

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 3111 B ~ Metals in Water by FLAA- Direct Air-Acetylene Flame
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 445.0 ~ EPA; Chlorophyll and Pheophytin in Algae by Fluorescence
LaboratoryName: Cascade Research Group

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 3111 B ~ Metals in Water by FLAA- Direct Air-Acetylene Flame
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 3111 B ~ Metals in Water by FLAA- Direct Air-Acetylene Flame
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 3111 B ~ Metals in Water by FLAA- Direct Air-Acetylene Flame
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 3111 B ~ Metals in Water by FLAA- Direct Air-Acetylene Flame
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4110 B ~ Anions in Water by Ion Chromatography
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4110 B ~ Anions in Water by Ion Chromatography
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

ProjectName: Lake Monitoring in Klamath Network Parks
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 3111 B ~ Metals in Water by FLAA- Direct Air-Acetylene Flame
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 3111 B ~ Metals in Water by FLAA- Direct Air-Acetylene Flame
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

ProjectName: Lake Monitoring in Klamath Network Parks
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4500 NO3 F ~ Nitrate in Water- Automated Cadmium Reduction
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
ProjectName: Lake Monitoring in Klamath Network Parks
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 445.0 ~ EPA; Chlorophyll and Pheophytin in Algae by Fluorescence
LaboratoryName: Cascade Research Group

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4500 P F ~ Phosphorus in Water by Colorimetry Automated Ascorbic Acid Method
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4110 B ~ Anions in Water by Ion Chromatography
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 3111 B ~ Metals in Water by FLAA- Direct Air-Acetylene Flame
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
ProjectName: Stream Monitoring in Klamath Network Parks
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4110 B ~ Anions in Water by Ion Chromatography
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 3111 D ~ Metals in Water by FLAA- Direct Nitrous Oxide-Acetylene Flame
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 5310 B ~ Total Organic Carbon by Combustion-Infrared Method
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 3111 B ~ Metals in Water by FLAA- Direct Air-Acetylene Flame
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 5310 B ~ Total Organic Carbon by Combustion-Infrared Method
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4500 NO3 F ~ Nitrate in Water- Automated Cadmium Reduction
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
ProjectName: Stream Monitoring in Klamath Network Parks
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4500 P F ~ Phosphorus in Water by Colorimetry Automated Ascorbic Acid Method
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4500 P F ~ Phosphorus in Water by Colorimetry Automated Ascorbic Acid Method
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4110 B ~ Anions in Water by Ion Chromatography
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4110 B ~ Anions in Water by Ion Chromatography
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 5310 B ~ Total Organic Carbon by Combustion-Infrared Method
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4500 NO3 F ~ Nitrate in Water- Automated Cadmium Reduction
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 5310 B ~ Total Organic Carbon by Combustion-Infrared Method
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

ProjectName: Lake Monitoring in Klamath Network Parks
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4110 B ~ Anions in Water by Ion Chromatography
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 445.0 ~ EPA; Chlorophyll and Pheophytin in Algae by Fluorescence
LaboratoryName: Cascade Research Group

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4110 B ~ Anions in Water by Ion Chromatography
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

ProjectName: Lake Monitoring in Klamath Network Parks
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 3111 B ~ Metals in Water by FLAA- Direct Air-Acetylene Flame
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 3111 B ~ Metals in Water by FLAA- Direct Air-Acetylene Flame
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.

This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4500 P F ~ Phosphorus in Water by Colorimetry Automated Ascorbic Acid Method
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water sample collection for streams is a relatively simple affair: (1) Ensure that the sample point is at a well mixed cross-section (done in SOP #7: Water Quality Multiprobe Calibration and Field Measurements); (2) Ensure that no crew members have entered the stream above the collection point; (3) Precondition the 2 L amber high density polyethylene collection vial by immersing the vial under the water surface, allowing approximately 0.5 L to enter. Loosely screw the lid and shake vigorously. This should allow some water to splash out the threads of the bottle; (4) Dump the preconditioning water away from the processing area; and (5) Re-immerse the bottle at the sample point, allowing the water to completely fill the bottle. Cap the lid, place in the shade, and prepare for processing.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4500 P F ~ Phosphorus in Water by Colorimetry Automated Ascorbic Acid Method
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo
